===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|hamer}}, {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|hamor}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*hamaraz}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{m|fy|hammer}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{m|nds|Hamer}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|hamer}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Hammer}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|da|hammer}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{m|sv|hammare}}).
The Germanic ''*hamaraz'' "tool with a stone head" derives from a {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*h₂eḱmoros}} (compare Sanskrit {{m|sa|अश्मरी||strangury}}), itself a derivation from {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éḱmō||stone}}.

For {{m|ine-pro|*h₂éḱmō||stone}}, compare {{etyl|lt|-}} {{m|lt|akmuõ}}, {{etyl|ru|-}} {{m|ru|камень}}, {{etyl|sh|-}} {{m|sh|kamēn}}, {{etyl|sq|-}} {{m|sq|kmesë||sickle}}, {{etyl|grc|-}} {{m|grc|ἄκμων||meteor rock, anvil}}, {{etyl|ae|-}} {{term|tr=asman|lang=ae}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|अश्मन्|tr=aśman|lang=sa|sc=Deva}}) (root {{m|ine-pro|*h₂eḱ-||sharp}}).

